      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>meta description</strong> is an HTML attribute placed in a page's <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> section that summarizes the page's content in 150-160 characters. It appears as the descriptive text below the clickable title in Google search results. It is your page's elevator pitch to a searcher deciding whether to click your result or scroll past it.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Optimal length</div>
            <div class="tms-value">140-155 characters</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">On-Page SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Google rewrites</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~62% of the time</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">SEO impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Indirect (via CTR)</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">A personal injury law firm with the description "Injured in a car accident in Phoenix? Our attorneys have recovered $50M+ for accident victims" consistently outperforms generic competitors in click-through rate — not because of rankings, but because the description makes clicking the obvious next move. One ecommerce brand improved CTR from 2.1% to 4.8% purely by rewriting meta descriptions. That's not a minor optimization.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a meta description?</h2>
        <p>A meta description is an HTML meta element that lives in the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> section of a page. Its syntax:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment">&lt;!-- In your page's &lt;head&gt; section --&gt;</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">&lt;meta</span> <span class="uf-new">name="description"</span><br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="uf-new">content="Your 140-155 character summary of the page here."</span><span class="uf-label">&gt;</span>
        </div>

        <p>In Google search results, this content appears below the page title (the blue link) and the URL. It's one of three visible elements a searcher uses to decide whether to click:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>The title tag (blue clickable headline)</li>
          <li>The URL (shown in green or grey beneath the title)</li>
          <li>The meta description (the snippet text)</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Most CMS platforms — WordPress, Webflow, Ghost, Shopify — have dedicated fields for meta descriptions, so you don't need to edit HTML directly. SEO plugins like Yoast or RankMath surface this field clearly.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's use of your description</div>
          <p>Google displays your written meta description when it's relevant to the query being searched. Ahrefs research found Google rewrites descriptions <strong>approximately 62% of the time</strong> — usually pulling text from elsewhere on the page that better matches the specific search query. Writing good descriptions still matters: the 38% that display as written are your highest-intent clicks.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why meta descriptions matter for SEO</h2>
        <p>Meta descriptions are not a direct ranking factor — Google confirmed this. Their influence on SEO is indirect but measurable:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Click-through rate lift.</strong> A description that matches searcher intent and clearly communicates value earns more clicks. Higher CTR tells Google's ranking algorithm that your page is satisfying searchers — which can improve rankings over time.</li>
          <li><strong>Keyword bolding.</strong> When your description contains words that match the search query, Google bolds them. Bold text catches the eye and increases CTR. Including the primary keyword naturally in your description earns this bolding automatically.</li>
          <li><strong>Reduces bounce rate.</strong> A description that accurately represents your page sets correct expectations. Searchers who click already know what they're getting — they're less likely to immediately return to the search results page.</li>
          <li><strong>Social sharing preview.</strong> Facebook, LinkedIn, and Slack use meta descriptions (via Open Graph tags or the meta description fallback) to generate link previews. A compelling description improves click-through from social shares too.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How meta descriptions work in search results</h2>
        <p>Understanding how Google decides what to display helps you write descriptions that actually appear:</p>

        <h3>When Google uses your description</h3>
        <p>Google uses your written meta description when it closely matches the query being searched. If someone searches for "best standing desks 2026" and your description says "Compare 2026's best standing desks rated by ergonomics, build quality, and price" — Google will likely display it because it directly addresses the query.</p>

        <h3>When Google rewrites your description</h3>
        <p>Google generates its own snippet when: your description doesn't match the specific query variation being searched, your description is too short or too long, or your description is duplicate across multiple pages. Google pulls the rewritten text from the page body — typically from a paragraph that closely answers the query.</p>

        <h3>Character limits that matter</h3>
        <p>Google truncates displayed descriptions at approximately 155-160 characters on desktop and 120 characters on mobile. Descriptions that exceed these limits get cut mid-sentence with "..." — which loses the call-to-action or key detail at the end.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Meta description types by page type</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Page type</th><th>Best approach</th><th>Example pattern</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Blog post</strong></td>
                <td>Lead with the answer or key takeaway</td>
                <td>"Learn how [X] works and [benefit]. 5-minute guide with [specific detail]."</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Product page</strong></td>
                <td>Benefits + specific differentiator + CTA</td>
                <td>"[Product]: [key benefit]. [Differentiator vs. competitors]. Free shipping."</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Service page</strong></td>
                <td>What you do + who you serve + result</td>
                <td>"[Service] for [audience]. [Specific outcome]. [Trust signal]."</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Homepage</strong></td>
                <td>What you do + for whom + primary CTA</td>
                <td>"[Company] helps [audience] [achieve outcome]. [Key differentiator]. [CTA]."</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Local business</strong></td>
                <td>Service + city + trust signal</td>
                <td>"[Service] in [City]. [Years/clients/award]. Call for a free quote."</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real meta description examples and their impact</h2>

        <h3>1. Personal injury law firm — benefit-led with specifics</h3>
        <p>A competitor's description: <em>"Injured in a car accident in Phoenix? Our attorneys have recovered $50M+ for accident victims. Free consultation."</em> This works because it addresses the searcher's situation directly, includes a specific trust signal ($50M+), and closes with a low-friction CTA (free consultation). It earned significantly higher CTR than generic "experienced attorneys in Phoenix" descriptions.</p>

        <h3>2. Ecommerce standing desks — CTR doubled</h3>
        <p>Before: <em>"Shop standing desks online. Free shipping available."</em> After: <em>"Compare 2026's best standing desks rated by ergonomics, build quality, and price. 60-day trial."</em> CTR increased from 2.1% to 4.8%. The rewrite added query-matching language, a specific differentiator (comparison angle), and a risk-reducer (60-day trial).</p>

        <h3>3. SaaS blog content — 15% average CTR lift</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company audited 200 blog posts with auto-generated meta descriptions and rewrote every one. Average organic CTR across those pages increased by 15% over the following 60 days, with no other changes to the pages. At scale, CTR improvements compound into meaningful traffic gains without additional link building or content creation.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Meta description vs. title tag — what each does</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Meta description: sell the click</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>150-160 character summary below the title</li>
              <li>Indirect SEO impact through CTR</li>
              <li>Not a direct ranking signal</li>
              <li>Optimizes the decision to click</li>
              <li>Google rewrites 62% of the time</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Title tag: earn the ranking</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>50-60 character clickable headline</li>
              <li>Direct ranking factor for Google</li>
              <li>Must include primary keyword</li>
              <li>Determines which queries you rank for</li>
              <li>Google rewrites less frequently (~50%)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 meta description best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Include the primary keyword naturally.</strong> When your description matches the search query, Google bolds those words in the result — catching the eye and improving CTR. Don't stuff keywords; one natural inclusion is enough.</li>
          <li><strong>Write unique descriptions for every page.</strong> Duplicate descriptions across multiple pages waste the opportunity to target different queries and tell Google those pages have distinct value.</li>
          <li><strong>Lead with the benefit or direct answer.</strong> Search results are scanned, not read. The first phrase of your description determines whether the searcher keeps reading. State the most compelling thing first.</li>
          <li><strong>Include a call to action when appropriate.</strong> "Free consultation," "Compare now," "See the full guide" — action phrases at the end of a description tell the searcher what happens next and increase clicks.</li>
          <li><strong>Stay at 140-155 characters.</strong> Use a character counter. Descriptions truncated at 155 characters with "..." lose their closing hook — usually the CTA or key differentiator.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor CTR in Google Search Console.</strong> Go to Search Console → Performance → Pages, sort by CTR. Pages with high impressions but low CTR (under 2-3%) are priority candidates for description rewrites.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — writing descriptions for Google, not the searcher</div>
          <p>Stuffing the primary keyword multiple times or writing descriptions that read like a keyword list ("seo services, seo company, seo agency") doesn't improve performance. Google rewards descriptions that match searcher intent and earn clicks — not keyword density. Write for the person scanning the search result page.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common meta description mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>No meta description at all</strong> — leaving it blank lets Google pull any text from the page, often a navigation item or sidebar text that doesn't represent the page value.</li>
          <li><strong>Duplicate descriptions across pages</strong> — identical descriptions give Google no signal of each page's distinct value and waste CTR optimization opportunities.</li>
          <li><strong>Exceeding 160 characters</strong> — the description gets truncated mid-sentence on most devices, cutting off the most important part (usually the CTA at the end).</li>
          <li><strong>Keyword stuffing</strong> — doesn't help rankings and produces unnatural-sounding snippets that reduce CTR.</li>
          <li><strong>Generic descriptions</strong> — "Welcome to our website. We offer quality services" gives the searcher no reason to click over competitors with specific, compelling descriptions.</li>
          <li><strong>Not updating after content changes</strong> — meta descriptions go stale when page content changes. An outdated description that no longer matches the page earns a Google rewrite — and the rewrite might not be as good as yours could be.</li>
        </ul>

